description:
It's being called new age of drone wars - it's being called Russia's Pearl Harbour.
Whether Russia hits back big - one thing is certain - we will never see wars the same way again. The age of big guns / jets / carriers is over - the new age of small / agile / AI assisted drones is here. Today it's Ukraine - tomorrow it could be China or Pakistan. Are we anywhere close to ready?

comments.text:
Don’t blindly absorb the narratives pushed by mainstream news outlets many of them oversimplify the complex geopolitical dynamics at play. The Russia-Ukraine war, from Moscow’s perspective, isn’t just about territorial ambition but is rooted in decades of NATO’s perceived hypocrisy & strategic overreach. After the Cold War, Western leaders allegedly gave verbal assurances that NATO wouldn’t expand eastward. Yet over the years, NATO has steadily absorbed former Warsaw Pact countries & even ex-Soviet republics moves Russia views as a direct violation of those understandings & a threat to its national security.
Ukraine, given its deep historical, cultural & geographic significance to Russia, was seen as a red line. The possibility of Ukraine joining NATO ignited serious alarm in Moscow. The 2014 ousting of Ukraine’s pro-Russian president is still considered by Russia as a Western-backed coup, reinforcing its fear of being encircled. Russia also highlights the West’s double standards pointing to interventions in Iraq, Libya & Kosovo as evidence that NATO disregards international norms when it suits their interests. In 2021, Russia proposed formal security guarantees to halt NATO’s eastward expansion proposals flatly rejected, further fueling tensions.
The recent Ukrainian drone attacks deep into Russian territory are now pushing the conflict into far more dangerous territory. These provocations won’t go unanswered. If Kyiv & its allies believe such tactics will wear Russia down, they gravely misjudge Moscow’s resolve. This isn’t a war that will end through media spin or symbolic strikes. If the West dares to compare this with Pearl Harbor, it must also be prepared for consequences resembling another Hiroshima. Russia remains a nuclear power with vast military capabilities underestimating its power would be not just foolish, but catastrophic. Understanding this conflict demands more than one-sided headlines; it requires an honest look at the history, power plays & broken assurances that led to this flashpoint.
